ngual secondary knowledge base that collects structured data—items identified by Q‑numbers, each with labels, descriptions, aliases, and statements composed of P‑numbered properties and values—to support Wikipedia, other Wikimedia projects, and any external applications. Items are centrally stored in the Wikidata repository, linked to each other, to external identifiers, and to corresponding pages on client wikis via sitelinks, allowing the same data to be displayed in any language and kept up‑to‑date across all projects. Users and bots can create, edit, and query this data through built‑in tools (e.g., the Query Service), APIs, or Lua interfaces, making the information readily reusable worldwide.', 'append': False, 'trailing_newline': True, 'leading_newline': False}, 'interacted_element': None}, {'go_to_url': {'url': 'https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Wikidata:Tour', 'new_tab': False}, 'interacted_element': None}, {'write_file': {'file_name': 'intro_summary.md', 'content': 'Wikidata is a free, collaborative, multilingual secondary knowledge base that stores structured data as items (Q‑numbers) with labels, descriptions, aliases, and statements using properties (P‑numbers). Items are linked to each other, external identifiers, and sitelinks to Wikimedia projects, enabling consistent data across languages. Users and bots can create, edit, and query this data via built‑in tools, APIs, and the Query Service.', 'append': False, 'trailing_newline': True, 'leading_newline': False}, 'interacted_element': None}, {'write_file': {'file_name': 'tours_summary.md', 'content': 'Wikidata Tours are interactive tutorials that demonstrate how Wikidata works and teach users how to add data. They cover basics such as the overall structure, items, and statements, each lasting about five minutes and providing hands‑on editing practice. Starting a tour requires an account or logs the IP, but it offers a practical way to learn the concepts and editing workflow.', 'append': False, 'trailing_newline': True, 'leading_newline': False}, 'interacted_element': None}, {'write_file': {'file_name': 'results.md', 'content': 'The best way to learn about Wikidata\'s structure and concepts using only the Wikidata site is to first read the Introduction page for a concise overview of items, properties, statements, and sitelinks, and then complete the Wikidata Tours, especially the "Wikidata Basics" and "Items" tutorials. The tours provide hands‑on, step‑by‑step guidance on how the data model works and how to edit items, reinforcing the concepts from the Introduction. Together, these resources give both theoretical understanding and practical experience, making them the most effective learning path.', 'append': False, 'trailing_newline': True, 'leading_newline': False}, 'interacted_element': None}, {'done': {'text': 'The best way to learn about Wikidata\'s structure and concepts using only the Wikidata site is to first read the Introduction page for a concise overview of items, properties, statements, and sitelinks, and then complete the Wikidata Tours, especially the "Wikidata Basics" and "Items" tutorials. The tours provide hands‑on, step‑by‑step guidance on how the data model works and how to edit items, reinforcing the concepts from the Introduction. Together, these resources give both theoretical understanding and practical experience, making them the most effective learning path.', 'success': True, 'files_to_display': ['results.md']}, 'interacted_element': None}])
